data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, for modern .NET the idiomatic replacement for manual thread management is `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you automatic thread-pool management and is the recommended pattern, but it's an **improvement**, not a required migration step. Your existing code will compile and run correctly on .NET 8 as-is.
